&gt; I&#39;m from Ontario, and I can see that I may gravitate to #34 and not 
&gt; worry too much about the subtleties of #32 and #33. There are some 
&gt; minor differences in how I pronounce those, but #34 does the trick in 
&gt; most cases. I am preserving #32+#25 as I find it easier to write, and 
&gt; I just treat it as a single sound.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; /Hi John,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Since you&#39;re starting out I want to recommend taking a careful look 
&gt; at your usage of #32/33/34: These represent three different sounds in 
&gt; British English which have largely converged in American and Canadian 
&gt; English. If you&#39;re from Ontario, then I&#39;m guessing that your 
&gt; pronunciation is extremely similar to mine in California.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The vowel which letter #33 represents is basically the same as for 
&gt; #32, except that with #33 you&#39;re also rounding your lips. (Most people 
&gt; don&#39;t realize that.) The sound of letter #33 occurs frequently in 
&gt; Britain, as well as New York / New Jersey / New England. In my 
&gt; pronunciation the #33 never occurs at all, as it&#39;s totally replaced by 
&gt; #32. In my speaking the sound of #34 is also almost completely 
&gt; replaced by #32; I have the #32 sound only before an &quot;l&quot; or an &quot;r&quot;, 
&gt; and in dipthongs (in which case it&#39;s not written in QS, of course, 
&gt; since it has specific letters for diphthongs).
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Anyway, just want to encourage you to look carefully at those, 
&gt; regardless of what conclusions you reach.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Kind Regards,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Scott
